Both confirmed. Reminder doesn't apply — task complete.

# B1 PoC Results — Cross-project assignee + user-existence oracle

## Result summary

| Test | Attacker | Endpoint | Body | Expected | Observed |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Cross-project assign | `kavya` (Q3 Launch member) | `PATCH /api/tasks/<q3-task>` | `{"assigneeId":"<lina-id>"}` | 400/403 — "user is not a member of this project" | **HTTP 200**; DB shows task assigned to Lina with `is_project_member = f` |
| Oracle: real userId (lina) | kavya | same | `{"assigneeId":"cmp3q9s0c0004mh5rl6z7wdkx"}` | (any deterministic response) | **HTTP 200** |
| Oracle: bogus userId | kavya | same | `{"assigneeId":"cwhatever-not-a-real-userid"}` | (same deterministic response) | **HTTP 500** (Prisma FK violation) |
| Oracle: real userId (dev) | kavya | same | `{"assigneeId":"cmp3q9s0c0003mh5r5o97t1mv"}` | (same deterministic response) | **HTTP 200** |

## What this proves

### B1.1 — Cross-project assignee

Server-side DB cross-check after a single attacker PATCH:

```
id           = cmp3q9s0i000vmh5rz1llbkls
title        = Prepare customer email blast
assignee_id  = cmp3q9s0c0004mh5rl6z7wdkx
assignee_email = lina@example.com
project_name = Q3 Launch
is_project_member = f      ← Lina has no membership on Q3 Launch
```

`PATCH /api/tasks/:id` accepted the assignment with no check that the assignee belongs to the project. Lina is now nominally responsible for a Q3 Launch task — visible in the UI, queryable through the API — despite never having been added to Q3 Launch.

### B1.2 — User-existence oracle

Same endpoint serves as a yes/no oracle on whether a candidate `userId` exists in the `users` table:

- Real id → 200 OK.
- Nonexistent id → 500 (Prisma raises P2003, the route doesn't catch).

The attacker doesn't need to know what column failed — just the difference between 200 and 500 is enough to enumerate.

## Why both happen — same line of code

[src/schemas/task.ts:13-19](src/schemas/task.ts#L13-L19) accepts `assigneeId` without scoping:

```ts
export const updateTaskSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1).max(200).optional(),
  description: z.string().max(5000).nullable().optional(),
  status: taskStatusSchema.optional(),
  assigneeId: z.string().nullable().optional(),   // ← any string, no membership check
  position: z.number().int().min(0).optional(),
});
```

…and [src/app/api/tasks/[id]/route.ts:29-31](src/app/api/tasks/[id]/route.ts#L29-L31) hands the parsed data straight to `prisma.task.update`. No "is this assignee a member of the task's project" check, no try/catch around the FK violation that the bogus-id case raises.

## Compounding effect

- **+ A1 (IDOR on PATCH)** — already proven in [IDOR_AND_HASH_LEAK_AUDIT.md](IDOR_AND_HASH_LEAK_AUDIT.md): no membership check on PATCH at all. So a totally unaffiliated authenticated user can not only edit any task, they can also assign it to any user *and* use the same endpoint as an oracle. There is no rate limit on this — see the earlier login-bruteforce demonstration; the same lack of throttling applies.
- **+ Information leak in the PATCH response body** — the response includes `include: { assignee: { select: { id, name, email } } }` ([tasks/[id]/route.ts:32-34](src/app/api/tasks/[id]/route.ts#L32-L34)). So a successful 200 also returns the assignee's name + email to the attacker. The oracle isn't just yes/no; it's a `userId → {name, email}` lookup.

## Fix

Tighten the schema *and* the handler. Schema-level coverage:

```ts
// no schema change strictly required, but adding a refine() that runs server-side
// validation against project membership is the cleanest single place
```

Handler-level coverage (recommended — combines well with the A1 fix):

```ts
export async function PATCH(req: NextRequest, { params }: Params) {
  const user = await getCurrentUser(req);
  if (!user) return unauthorized();
  const { id } = await params;
  const body = await req.json().catch(() => null);
  const parsed = updateTaskSchema.safeParse(body);
  if (!parsed.success) return badRequest("invalid input", parsed.error.flatten());

  const existing = await prisma.task.findUnique({ where: { id } });
  if (!existing) return notFound("task not found");

  // A1 fix
  const membership = await getProjectMembership(user.id, existing.projectId);
  if (!membership) return forbidden("you are not a member of this project");
  if (!canEditTasks(membership.role)) return forbidden("viewers cannot edit tasks");

  // B1 fix — verify the proposed assignee is a member of the SAME project
  if (parsed.data.assigneeId) {
    const assigneeMembership = await getProjectMembership(parsed.data.assigneeId, existing.projectId);
    if (!assigneeMembership) {
      // Use 400, not 404 — do NOT leak whether the userId exists at all
      return badRequest("assignee must be a member of this project");
    }
  }

  const task = await prisma.task.update({ where: { id }, data: parsed.data, include: { … } });
  return NextResponse.json({ task });
}
```

Two things matter about the fix beyond just "add the check":

1. **Return 400 (not 404) for both "user doesn't exist" and "user exists but isn't a project member."** Use identical response bodies. Otherwise the oracle just moves from 200-vs-500 to 400-vs-200, and the attacker still learns existence.
2. **Wrap `prisma.task.update` in try/catch** for `P2003`/`P2025` so an unexpected FK violation can never leak existence via 500. Return a generic `badRequest`.

The same pattern should apply to `POST /api/projects/:id/tasks` ([projects/[id]/tasks/route.ts:73-86](src/app/api/projects/[id]/tasks/route.ts#L73-L86)) — it has the same `assigneeId` mass-assignment surface and the same missing membership check.

